    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-20T16:34:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-20T16:34:00-05:00" n="181"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–1554: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Republic of China</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d181fn1">Repeated for information to Geneva as telegram
                            <gloss target="#t_Tosec1">Tosec</gloss> 220, to Seoul as telegram 935,
                        and to Tokyo as telegram 2576. The file copy indicates that this message was
                        drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MCRJG1">McClurkin</persName> and approved
                        for transmission by <persName corresp="#p_DEF1">Drumright</persName> who
                        signed for <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-20T17:34:00-04:00"
                            >May 20, 1954—5:34 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>888. For Secretary <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName> from the
                    Secretary. Re Tokyo’s 2808 repeated Geneva <gloss target="#t_Tosec1"
                        >Tosec</gloss> 170, Seoul 925.<note n="2" xml:id="d181fn2">Dated May 15, not
                        printed. In it, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName>
                        suggested inclusion in any proposal for unification of Korea of a provision
                        for personal amnesty for all individuals; he indicated that Ambassador
                            <persName>Allison</persName> agreed with him. (396.1 GE/5–1554)</note>
                    Appreciate your valuable suggestion. Have transmitted it Geneva for information
                    US delegation there.</p>
                <p>So far as Korea is concerned our present problem is to secure some statement
                    basic principles upon which <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>, US and rest of
                    allied delegations can all agree. There seems little likelihood achieving any
                    political settlement disturbing present <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi> on any
                    basis which would be acceptable to us and prevent communist domination all
                    Korea. Nevertheless it may be useful at some point incorporate provision of
                    nature your suggestion in order demonstrate more clearly to world opinion our
                    effort achieve settlement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
